      <comment>added [[Category:Turkic history]] using [[WP:HC|HotCat]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Bilge Qaghan''',in Turkish Bilge Kağan. ([[Old Turkic]]: [[File:Old Turkic letter N1.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter G1.svg|10px]][[File:Old turkic letter Q.png|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter A.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter G2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter L2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter I.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter B2.svg|10px]], Bilge Kagan,&lt;ref&gt;[http://irq.kaznpu.kz/?lang=e&amp;mod=1&amp;tid=1&amp;oid=16&amp;m=1 Bilge kagan’s Memorial Complex, TÜRIK BITIG]&lt;/ref&gt; [[wikt:毗|毗]][[wikt:伽|伽]][[wikt:可|可]][[wikt:汗|汗]], [[Pinyin]]: píjiā kěhàn, [[Wade-Giles]]: p'i-chia k'o-han, official title: [[File:Old Turkic letter N1.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter G1.svg|10px]][[File:Old turkic letter Q.png|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter A.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter G2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter L2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter I.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter B2.svg|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter UK.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter R2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter U.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter T2.svg|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter SH.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter M.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter L1.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter O.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter B1.svg|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter A.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter D2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter I.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter R2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter NG.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter T2.svg|10px]] [[File:Old Turkic letter G2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter T2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter I.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter R2.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter NG.svg|10px]][[File:Old Turkic letter T2.svg|10px]], Teŋіriteg Тeŋiride bolmuš Türük Bilge qaγan,&lt;ref&gt;[http://irq.kaznpu.kz/index.php?l=t&amp;wi=726&amp;lang=e&amp;mod=3 Ethno Cultural Dictionary, TÜRIK BITIG]&lt;/ref&gt; personal name: 阿史那默棘連, āshǐnà mòjílián, a-shih-na mo-chi-lan) (683 or 684 - 734) was [[khagan]] of the [[Second Eastern Turkic Khaganate]]. His accomplishments are described in the [[Orkhon inscriptions]].

His name literally means &quot;wise chieftain&quot; in Turkic language. In 716, Qapaghan Qaghan was killed in his campaign against [[Tokuz-Oguzes|Toquz Oghuz]] and his severed head was send to [[Changan]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Tang194&quot;&gt;''[[Book of Tang]]'', [[:zh:s:舊唐書/卷194上|Vol. 194-I]]&lt;/ref&gt; [[Kul Tigin]] and [[Tonyukuk]] carried out a [[coup d'état]] against the previous ruler, his cousin [[Inel Qaghan]] who was son of [[Qapaghan Qaghan]]. They killed Qapaghan's son and brothers and made him a qaghan as Bilge Qaghan.&lt;ref name=&quot;Tang194&quot;/&gt;

Bilge's khaganate spanned vast steppes from the [[Caspian Sea]] to [[Manchuria]]; he also invaded the western sections of the [[China|Chinese]] territories. After his death from poisoning, several [[stela]]e were erected in [[Orkhon Valley|the capital area]] by the [[Orkhon River]]. These [[Orkhon inscriptions]] are the first known texts in the [[Old Turkic language]]. (Actually the popular name Orkhon inscriptions is out of date and most historians prefer the name [[Khöshöö Tsaidam Monuments]] inscriptions for the stelae of Bilge and Kul Tigin and [[Bain Tsokto]] for the earlier stelae of [[Tonyukuk]].)

He was poisoned by Buyruk Chor&lt;ref&gt;[http://mtad.humanity.ankara.edu.tr/IV-3_Eylul2007/240_47_MTAD4-3_EEkrem.pdf Erkin Ekrem, &quot;Sarı Uygurların Kökeni&quot;, ''Modern Türklük Araştırma Dergisi'', Vol. 4, No. 3, 2007, p. 175.]&lt;/ref&gt; (梅錄啜/梅录啜, méilù chuò, mei-lu-ch'o). He didn't die immediately and he had time to punish the family of Buyruk Chor with death.&lt;ref name=&quot;Tang194&quot;/&gt;

