The '''Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award''' ('''MVP''') is an annual [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) award given to one outstanding player in the [[American League|American]] and [[National League]]s. Since 1931, it has been awarded by the [[Baseball Writers Association of America]] (BBWAA). The winner receives the [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]] Memorial Baseball Award, which is named in honor of the first [[Commissioner of Baseball (MLB)|MLB commissioner]], who served from 1920 to 1944.&lt;ref name=&quot;ESPN 1763&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last=Gillette|first=Gary|coauthors=Palmer, Pete|title=The ESPN Baseball Encyclopedia|publisher=Sterling Publishing Co|location=New York City, New York|year=2007|edition=Fourth|page=1763|isbn=978-1-4027-4771-7}}&lt;/ref&gt; MVP voting takes place before the [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] but the results are not announced until after the [[World Series]]. The BBWAA began polling three writers in each league city in 1938, reducing that number to two per league city in 1961.&lt;ref name=&quot;ESPN&quot;&gt;Gillette &amp; Palmer, pp. 1764–1765&lt;/ref&gt;

[[First basemen]], with 34&amp;nbsp;winners, have won the most MVPs among [[infielder]]s, followed by [[second basemen]]&amp;nbsp;(16), [[third basemen]]&amp;nbsp;(15), and [[shortstop]]s&amp;nbsp;(14). Of the 23&amp;nbsp;[[pitcher]]s who have won the award, 14 are [[right-handed]] while nine are [[left-handed]]. [[Carl Hubbell]] and [[Hal Newhouser]] are the only pitchers to win multiple times, Newhouser winning consecutively in 1944 and 1945.&lt;ref name=&quot;BD 2000&quot;&gt;{{cite journal|date=December 2000|title=Major League Baseball's Most Valuable Player Award Winners|journal=Baseball Digest|publisher=Century Publishing Co.|location=Evanston, Illinois|volume=59|issue=12|pages=86–89|issn=0005-609X|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=my0DAAAAMBAJ&amp;pg=PA86#v=onepage&amp;q=&amp;f=false|accessdate=December 29, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; No pitcher has been named MVP since [[Dennis Eckersley]] in 1992. [[Hank Greenberg]], [[Stan Musial]], [[Alex Rodriguez]], and [[Robin Yount]] have won at different positions,&lt;ref name=&quot;BD 2000&quot; /&gt; while Rodriguez is the only player to win the award with two different teams at two different positions.&lt;ref name=&quot;Rodriguez&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/rodrial01.shtml|title=Alex Rodriguez Statistics|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Barry Bonds]] has won the most often&amp;nbsp;(seven times) and the most consecutively&amp;nbsp;(2001–2004).&lt;ref name=&quot;Bonds&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bondsba01.shtml|title=Barry Bonds Statistics|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Jimmie Foxx]] was the first player to win multiple times;&lt;ref name=&quot;Bonds&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/f/foxxji01.shtml|title=Jimmie Foxx Statistics|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; nine&amp;nbsp;players have won three times and 19 have won twice.&lt;ref name=&quot;winner list&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/mvp_cya.shtml|title=Most Valuable Player MVP Awards &amp; Cy Young Awards Winners|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 3, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The award's only tie occurred in the [[National League]] in 1979 when [[Keith Hernandez]] and [[Willie Stargell]] received an equal amount of points.&lt;ref name=&quot;BD 2000&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;1979 awards&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1979.shtml|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1979|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; There have been 17 unanimous winners, meaning they received all the first-place votes.&lt;ref name=&quot;ESPN&quot; /&gt; The [[New York Yankees]] have the most winning players with 22, followed by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] with 17&amp;nbsp;winners. Five franchises have not had a winner. The most recent recipients are [[Josh Hamilton (baseball)|Josh Hamilton]] in the [[American League]] and [[Joey Votto]] in the [[National League]].

